# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: by-product
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Animal wellbeing is highly dependent on feed that reflects a well balanced nutrition.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Some modern agricultural practices, such as fattening cows on grains or in feed lots, have detrimental effects on the environment and animals.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] For example, increased corn or other grain in feed for cows, makes their microbiomes more acidic weakening their immune systems and making cows a more likely vector for *E. coli*, while other feeding practices can improve animal impacts.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] For example, feeding cows certain kinds of seaweed, reduces their production of methane, reducing the greenhouse gases from meat production.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] When an environmental crisis strikes farmers or herders, such as a drought or extreme weather driven by climate change, farmers often have to shift to more expensive manufactured animal feed, which can negatively effect their economic viability.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] For example, a 2017 drought in Senegal reduced the availability of grazing lands leading to skyrocketing demand and prices for manufactured animal feed, causing farmers to sell large portions of their herds.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Additionally agriculture for producing animal feed puts pressure on land use: feed crops need land that otherwise might be used for human food and can be one of the driving factors for deforestation, soil degradation and climate change.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] "Fodder" refers particularly to foods or forages given to the animals (including plants cut and carried to them), rather than that which they forage for themselves.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] It includes hay, straw, silage, compressed and pelleted feeds, oils and mixed rations, and sprouted grains and legumes.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Grass and crop residues are the most important source of animal feed globally.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Grains account for 11% of the total dry matter consume by livestock at global level and oilseed crops by-products such as soybean cakes account for 5%.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The amount of grain used to produce the same unit of meat varies substantially between species and production systems.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] According to FAO, ruminants require an average of 2.8 kg of grains to produce 1 kg of meat while monogastrics require 3.2.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] These figures vary between 0.1 for extensive ruminant systems to 9.4 in beef feedlots, and from 0.1 in backyard chicken production to 4 in industrial pig production.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Farmed fish can also be fed on grain and use even less than poultry.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The two most important feed grains are maize and soybean, and the United States is by far the largest exporter of both, averaging about half of the global maize trade and 40% of the global soya trade in the years leading up the 2012 drought.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Other feed grains include wheat, oats, barley, and rice, among many others.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Traditional sources of animal feed include household food scraps and the byproducts of food processing industries such as milling and brewing.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Material remaining from milling oil crops like peanuts, soy, and corn are important sources of fodder.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Scraps fed to pigs are called slop, and those fed to chicken are called chicken scratch.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Brewer's spent grain is a byproduct of beer making that is widely used as animal feed.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Compound feed is fodder that is blended from various raw materials and additives.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] These blends are formulated according to the specific requirements of the target animal.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] They are manufactured by feed compounders as *meal type*, *pellets* or *crumbles*.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The main ingredients used in commercially prepared feed are the feed grains, which include corn, soybeans, sorghum, oats, and barley.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Compound feed may also include premixes, which may also be sold separately.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Premixes are composed of microingredients such as vitamins, minerals, chemical preservatives, antibiotics, fermentation products, and other ingredients that are purchased from premix companies, usually in sacked form, for blending into commercial rations.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Because of the availability of these products, farmers who use their own grain can formulate their own rations and be assured that their animals are getting the recommended levels of minerals and vitamins, although they are still subject to the Veterinary Feed Directive.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] According to the American Feed Industry Association, as much as $20 billion worth of feed ingredients are purchased each year.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] These products range from grain mixes to orange rinds and beet pulps.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The feed industry is one of the most competitive businesses in the agricultural sector and is by far the largest purchaser of U.S. corn, feed grains, and soybean meal.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Tens of thousands of farmers with feed mills on their own farms are able to compete with huge conglomerates with national distribution.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Feed crops generated $23.2 billion in cash receipts on U.S. farms in 2001.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] At the same time, farmers spent a total of $24.5 billion on feed that year.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] With progressing climate change and reoccurring droughts, extensive rangeland agriculture increasingly suffers of forage shortage.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Innovative approaches to substitute forage include the harvesting and processing of shrubs into animal feed.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] This has been extensively researched and applied in Namibia, using waste biomass resulting from woody encroachment.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] In 2011, around 734.5 million tons of feed were produced annually around the world.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The US Animal Drug Availability Act 1996, passed during the Clinton era, was the first attempt in that country to regulate the use of medicated feed.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] In 1997, in response to outbreaks of Bovine spongiform encephalopathy, commonly known as mad cow disease, the United States and Canada banned a range of animal tissues from cattle feed.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Feed bans in United States (2009) Canada (2007) expanded on this, prohibiting the use of potentially infectious tissue in all animal and pet food and fertilizers.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Forage is a plant material (mainly plant leaves and stems) eaten by grazing livestock.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Historically, the term *forage* has meant only plants eaten by the animals directly as pasture, crop residue, or immature cereal crops, but it is also used more loosely to include similar plants cut for fodder and carried to the animals, especially as hay or silage.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] While the term *forage* has a broad definition, the term *forage crop* is used to define crops, annual or biennial, which are grown to be utilized by grazing or harvesting as a whole crop.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Feed manufacturing refers to the process of producing animal feed from raw agricultural products.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Fodder produced by manufacturing is formulated to meet specific animal nutrition requirements for different species of animals at different life stages.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Create a formula: Nutritionists work side by side with scientists to formulate nutritionally sound and balanced diets for livestock, poultry, aquaculture and pets.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] This is a complex process, as every species has different nutritional requirements.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Mix ingredients: Once the formula is determined, the mill mixes the ingredients to create a finished product.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Package and label: Manufacturers determine the best way to ship the product.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] If it is prepared for retail, it will be "bagged and tagged," or placed into a bag with a label that includes the product's purpose, ingredients and instructions.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] If the product is prepared for commercial use, it will be shipped in bulk.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] In agriculture today, the nutritional needs of farm animals are well understood and may be satisfied through natural forage and fodder alone, or augmented by direct supplementation of nutrients in concentrated, controlled form.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The nutritional quality of feed is influenced not only by the nutrient content, but also by many other factors such as feed presentation, hygiene, digestibility, and effect on intestinal health.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Feed additives provide a mechanism through which these nutrient deficiencies can be resolved, improving animal rate of growth, health, and well-being.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Many farm animals have a diet largely consisting of grain-based ingredients because of the higher costs of quality feed.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Chelates in animal feed is jargon for metalloorganic compounds added to animal feed.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The compounds provide sources of various metals that improve the health or marketability of the animal.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Typical metal salts are derived from cobalt, copper, iron, manganese, and zinc.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The objective of supplementation with trace minerals is to avoid a variety of deficiency diseases.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Trace minerals carry out key functions in relation to many metabolic processes, most notably as cofactors for enzymes and hormones, and are essential for optimum health, growth and productivity.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] For example, supplementary minerals help ensure good growth, bone development, feathering in birds, hoof, skin and hair quality in mammals, enzyme structure and functions, and appetite.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Deficiency of trace minerals affects many metabolic processes and so may be manifested by different symptoms, such as poor growth and appetite, reproductive failures, impaired immune responses, and general ill-thrift.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] From the 1950s to the 1990s most trace mineral supplementation of animal diets was in the form of inorganic minerals, and these largely eradicated associated deficiency diseases in farm animals.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The role in fertility and reproductive diseases of dairy cattle highlights that organic forms of Zn are retained better than inorganic sources and so may provide greater benefit in disease prevention, notably mastitis and lameness.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Animals are thought to better absorb, digest, and use mineral chelates than inorganic minerals or simple salts.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] In theory lower concentrations of these minerals can be used in animal feeds.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] In addition, animals fed chelated sources of essential trace minerals excrete lower amounts in their faeces, and so there is less environmental contamination.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Insects may be able to supplement livestock feed, as they can transform low-value organic waste into nutritious products.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] On the other hand, insect production presents a number of unresolved environmental challenges.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Insect farms require constant heating at around 30 °C, resulting in high energy consumption.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] According to a study commissioned by the UK government, insects emit 5 to 13 times more greenhouse gases than soybean meal.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Their rearing consumes more water per kilogram than pork, chicken or beef, and most insects are fed on high-quality agricultural by-products rather than waste, putting them in direct competition with existing animal feed.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] The issue of local biodiversity risk if insects escape into the wild has also been raised.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Soybean meal is used in food and animal feeds, principally as a protein supplement, but also as a source of metabolizable energy.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] 60 lbs. or 27.2 kg) of soybeans yields 48 lbs.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Most soybean meal is defatted, produced as a co-product of soybean oil extraction.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Some, but not all, soybean meal contains ground soybean hulls.
[src:by-product/animal-feed] Soybean meal is heat-treated during production, to denature the trypsin inhibitors of soybeans, which would otherwise interfere with protein digestion.
[src:by-product/bagasse] The word comes from *bagasse* (French) and *bagazo* (Spanish), meaning *refuse* or *trash*.
[src:by-product/bagasse] It originally referred to the material left after pressing olives, palm nuts, and grapes.
[src:by-product/bagasse] The word eventually came to be used in the context of processing of plants such as sugarcane and sugar beets.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Today, it usually refers to by-products of the sugarcane mill.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Bagasse is the solid by-product when the liquid components are extracted from plants.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Much of the core of those plants is a heterogeneous "pith" fibre.
[src:by-product/bagasse] This fibre is primarily parenchyma tissue, along with bast, rind, or stem fibers of the sclerenchyma.
[src:by-product/bagasse] For every 10 tonnes of sugarcane crushed, a sugar factory produces nearly three tonnes of wet bagasse.
[src:by-product/bagasse] It is challenging to use this byproduct directly as a fuel because of the high moisture content, typically 40–50 percent.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Instead, bagasse is typically stored prior to further processing.
[src:by-product/bagasse] For electricity production, the bagasse is stored under moist conditions.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Under these conditions, the bagasse undergoes a mild exothermic process as the residual sugars slightly degrade.
[src:by-product/bagasse] For paper and pulp production, the bagasse is normally stored wet so as to facilitate the subsequent removal of any remaining sugar as well as the short pith fibres.
[src:by-product/bagasse] These fibres would impede the paper making process.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Numerous research efforts have explored using bagasse in the production of bio-based materials and as a biofuel in renewable power generation.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Sugarcane bagasse biomass (SB) has the potential to be transformed into energy, materials and chemicals.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Sugar mills often use bagasse as a primary fuel source.
[src:by-product/bagasse] When burned in quantity, bagasse produces enough heat energy to fully power a typical sugar mill, with some energy to spare.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Cogeneration is a common setup, with this extra energy sold to the consumer electrical grid.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Historically, bagasse was also used to fuel steam locomotives that brought the cut cane to the mills.
[src:by-product/bagasse] The CO2 emissions from burning the bagasse in a sugarcane plant is less than the amount of CO2 absorbed from the atmosphere when the sugarcane grows, which could make the process carbon-neutral or better.
[src:by-product/bagasse] In contrast, a study in the *International Journal of Global Warming* warned that electricity generation with bagasse would never be fully carbon-free but did represent a large reduction in carbon emissions compared to the use of diesel.
[src:by-product/bagasse] In countries such as Australia, sugar factories contribute this "green" power to the electricity grid.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Hawaiian Electric Industries also burns bagasse for cogeneration.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Ethanol produced from the sugar is a popular fuel in Brazil.
[src:by-product/bagasse] The cellulose-rich bagasse is also being investigated for its potential in producing commercial quantities of cellulosic ethanol.
[src:by-product/bagasse] For example, until May 2015, BP operated a cellulosic ethanol demonstration plant in Jennings, Louisiana.
[src:by-product/bagasse] In the Guangxi Zhuang Autonomous Region in China, bagasse is sometimes used to smoke bacon and sausages.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Bagasse from sugarcane production offers an attractive feedstock for the production of biofuel and value-added products as it does not affect food security.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Second generation biohydrogen, biomethane, biomethanol, or bioethanol through the biochemical route is considered to not only be an eco-friendly, but also economically feasible option.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Thermochemical production pathways, such as hydrothermal liquefaction, pyrolysis and gasification of bagasse are a promising alternative to produce advanced 2G biofuels (e.g. jet fuel and Diesel) and chemicals (e.g. for plastics) with low life cycle impacts.
[src:by-product/bagasse] In many tropical and subtropical countries such as India, China, Colombia, Iran, Thailand, and Argentina, bagasse is commonly used instead of wood in the production of pulp, paper and board.
[src:by-product/bagasse] This substitution produces pulp with physical properties that are well suited for printing and notebook paper, tissue products, boxes, and newspapers.
[src:by-product/bagasse] It can also be used for making boards resembling plywood or particle board, known as bagasse boards and Xanita boards.
[src:by-product/bagasse] These are widely used in the production of partitions and furniture.
[src:by-product/bagasse] The industrial steps to convert bagasse into paper were developed in 1937 at a small laboratory in Hacienda Paramonga, a sugar mill on the coast of Peru owned by the W.R.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Using a promising method invented by Clarence Birdseye, the company bought an old paper mill in Whippany, New Jersey and shipped bagasse from Peru there to test the viability of the process on an industrial scale.
[src:by-product/bagasse] The first bagasse paper manufacturing machines were designed in Germany and installed in the Cartavio sugar cane plant in 1938.
[src:by-product/bagasse] On January 26–27, 1950, the Noble & Wood Machine Company, the Kinsley Chemical Company, and the Chemical Paper Company jointly demonstrated the first successful commercial production of newsprint produced from bagasse at Chemical Paper's mills in Holyoke.
[src:by-product/bagasse] The process's first use was in the printing of a special edition of the *Holyoke Transcript-Telegram*.
[src:by-product/bagasse] This demonstration was done in collaboration with the governments of Puerto Rico and Argentina due to the economic importance of the product in countries without ready access to wood fibers.
[src:by-product/bagasse] The work was presented before representatives of 100 industrial interests and officials from 15 countries.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Bagasse has become a popular materials choice for tableware packaging.
[src:by-product/bagasse] The material is suitable for both cold and hot applications (up to ~120 °C).
[src:by-product/bagasse] Additionally, it can be put in the freezer and microwave without problems.
[src:by-product/bagasse] It also has reasonably good water- and grease resistance, which can be enhanced by chemical modification.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Historically, PFOA and related fluorinated materials were commonly used to increase heat, water and grease resistance.
[src:by-product/bagasse] However, the use of these have now been banned.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Other means of enhancing the material properties of bagasse are mixing with gelatin, starch or agar.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Nanocellulose, a higher-value product, can be produced from bagasse through various conventional and novel processes.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Workplace exposure to dust from the processing of bagasse can cause bagassosis, a subtype of the chronic lung condition pulmonary fibrosis.
[src:by-product/bagasse] Sugarcane fiber, a variety of processed bagasse, is sometimes added to human food.
[src:by-product/bagasse] It is a soluble fiber that can help promote intestinal regularity.
[src:by-product/bagasse] One animal study suggests that sugarcane fiber combined with a high-fat diet may help control type 2 diabetes.
[src:by-product/bagasse] It is a good source of lignoceric and cerotic acids.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Most bottom ash generated at U.S. power plants is stored in ash ponds, which can cause serious environmental damage if they experience structural failures.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] In a conventional water-impounded hopper (WIH) system, the clinker lumps get crushed to small sizes by clinker grinders mounted under water and fall down into a trough, where a water ejector takes them out to a sump.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] From there, it is pumped out by suitable rotary pumps.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] In another arrangement, a continuous link chain scrapes out the clinkers from under water and feeds them to clinker grinders outside the bottom ash hopper.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Modern municipal waste incinerators reduce the production of dioxins by incinerating at 850 to 950 degrees Celsius for at least two seconds, forming incinerator bottom ash as byproduct.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] In United States facilities, the ash waste is typically pumped to ash ponds, the most common disposal method.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Some power plants operate a dry disposal system with landfills.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] In the United States, coal ash is a major component of the nation's industrial waste stream.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] In 2017, 38.2 million short tons (34.7×10^6 t) of fly ash, and 9.7 million short tons (8.8×10^6 t) of bottom ash, were generated.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Coal contains trace levels of arsenic, barium, beryllium, boron, cadmium, chromium, thallium, selenium, molybdenum, and mercury, many of which are highly toxic to humans and other life.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Coal ash, a product of combustion, concentrates these elements and can contaminate groundwater or surface waters if there are leaks from an ash pond.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Most U.S. power plants do not use geomembranes, leachate collection systems, or other flow controls often found in municipal solid waste landfills.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Following a 2008 failure that caused the Tennessee Valley Authority's Kingston Fossil Plant coal fly ash slurry spill, the U.S.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) began developing regulations that would apply to all ash ponds in the U.S.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] The EPA published its "Part A" final rule for Coal Combustion Residuals (CCR) on August 28, 2020, requiring all unlined ash ponds to retrofit with liners or close by April 11, 2021.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Some facilities may apply to obtain additional time—up to 2028—to find alternatives for managing ash wastes before closing their surface impoundments.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] EPA published its "CCR Part B" rule on November 12, 2020, which would allow certain facilities to use an alternative liner, based on a demonstration that human health and the environment will not be affected.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Further litigation on the CCR regulation is pending as of 2021.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] In 2020, several facilities applied for alternate liner demonstrations under the Part B rule.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] EPA has not made final determinations on the applications as of early 2026.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Bottom ash can be extracted, cooled, and conveyed using dry ash handling technology.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] When left dry, the ash can be used to make concrete, bricks, and other useful materials.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] There are also several environmental benefits.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] Bottom ash may be used as raw alternative material, replacing earth or sand or aggregates, for example in road construction and in cement kilns (clinker production).
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] A noticeable other use is as growing medium in horticulture (usually after sieving).
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] In the United Kingdom it is known as furnace bottom ash (FBA), to distinguish it from incinerator bottom ash (IBA), the non-combustible elements remaining after incineration.
[src:by-product/bottom-ash] A pioneer use of bottom ash was in the production of concrete blocks used to construct many high-rise flats in London in the 1960s.
[src:by-product/bran] Bran is present in cereal grain, including rice, corn (maize), wheat, oats, barley, rye, and millet.
[src:by-product/bran] Bran is not the same as chaff, which is a coarser, scaly material surrounding the grain and is indigestible by humans.
[src:by-product/bran] Bran is particularly rich in dietary fiber and essential fatty acids, and contains significant quantities of starch, protein, vitamins, and dietary minerals.
[src:by-product/bran] It is also a source of phytic acid, an antinutrient that prevents nutrient absorption.
[src:by-product/bran] The high oil content of bran makes it subject to rancidification, one of the reasons that it is often separated from the grain before storage or further processing.
[src:by-product/bran] Bran is often heat-treated to increase its shelf life.
[src:by-product/bran] Rice bran is a byproduct of the rice-milling process (the conversion of brown rice to white rice), and it contains various antioxidants.
[src:by-product/bran] A major rice bran fraction contains 12%–13% oil and highly unsaponifiable components (4.3%).
[src:by-product/bran] This fraction contains tocotrienols (a form of vitamin E), gamma-oryzanol, and beta-sitosterol; all these constituents may contribute to the lowering of the plasma levels of the various parameters of the lipid profile.
[src:by-product/bran] Rice bran also contains a high level of dietary fiber (beta-glucan, pectin, and gum).
[src:by-product/bran] It also contains ferulic acid, which is also a component of the structure of nonlignified cell walls.
[src:by-product/bran] Some research suggests, however, that inorganic arsenic is present at some level in rice bran.
[src:by-product/bran] One study found the levels to be 20% higher than in contaminated drinking water.
[src:by-product/bran] Bran is often used to enrich breads (notably muffins) and breakfast cereals, especially for the benefit of those wishing to increase their intake of dietary fiber.
[src:by-product/bran] Bran may also be used for pickling (*nukazuke*) as in the *tsukemono* of Japan, as well as in the production of East Asian black vinegars.
[src:by-product/bran] Rice bran in particular finds many uses in Japan, where it is known as *nuka* (糠; ぬか).
[src:by-product/bran] Besides using it for pickling, Japanese people add it to the water when boiling bamboo shoots, and use it for dish washing.
[src:by-product/bran] In Kitakyushu City, it is called *jinda* and used for stewing fish, such as sardines.
[src:by-product/bran] Wheat bran is useful as feed for poultry and other livestock, as part of a balanced ration with other inputs.
[src:by-product/bran] Wheatings, a milling byproduct comprising mostly bran with some pieces of endosperm also left over, are included in this category.
[src:by-product/bran] Bran oil may be also extracted for use by itself for industrial purposes (such as in the paint industry), or as a cooking oil, such as rice bran oil.
[src:by-product/bran] Bran was found to be the most successful slug deterrent by BBC's TV programme *Gardeners' World*.
[src:by-product/bran] It is a common substrate and food source used for feeder insects, such as mealworms and waxworms.
[src:by-product/bran] Wheat bran has also been used for tanning leather since at least the 16th century.
[src:by-product/bran] As with cereal fibers and whole grain consumption, bran is under preliminary research for the potential to improve nutrition and affect chronic diseases.
[src:by-product/bran] The authors recommended that heat treatment should be sufficient to achieve selective lipase inactivation, but not so much as to render the polar lipids oxidizable upon prolonged storage.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Buttermilk is consumed as a beverage and used in cooking.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Drinking buttermilk remains common in warmer climates where unrefrigerated milk sours quickly, as the fermentation prevents further spoilage.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] In making soda bread, the acid in fermented buttermilk reacts with the leavening agent, sodium bicarbonate (baking soda), to produce carbon dioxide.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Buttermilk is used in marination, especially for chicken and pork.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Buttermilk originated before the advent of refrigeration and homogenization, when fresh raw milk was left to stand for a period of time to allow the cream to separate to the top.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] During the separation period, naturally occurring lactic acid-producing bacteria in the milk ferment it, which facilitates the butter churning process, because fat from cream with a lower pH coalesces more readily than that of fresh cream.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] As this acidic environment also helps prevent potentially harmful microorganisms from growing, shelf life is increased.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] This traditional method is susceptible to spoilage during the fermenting and churning processes, particularly under poor hygiene standards and when it is not kept cool.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Refrigeration and the use of fresh milk in near-aseptically clean dairies largely eliminated these problems.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Traditional buttermilk is still common in many households across South Asia, the Middle East, and various parts of Europe but is seldom found in other Western countries.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] In Arab culture, buttermilk is commonly sold ice cold with other dairy products and often consumed during Ramadan for *iftar* and *suhur*, while in the Indian subcontinent, it may be served with roasted maize.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] The lactic acid is the product of the bacteria fermenting lactose, the primary sugar in milk.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] As the bacteria produce lactic acid, the pH of the milk decreases and casein, the primary milk protein, precipitates, causing the curdling or clabbering of milk, making cultured buttermilk thicker than plain milk.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] While both traditional and cultured buttermilk contain lactic acid, traditional buttermilk is thinner than cultured buttermilk.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Cultured buttermilk was first commercially introduced in the United States in the 1920s.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] It was initially consumed among immigrants.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Consumption of buttermilk has declined since then, and annual sales in 2012 reached less than half that number.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] However, condensed buttermilk and dried buttermilk remain common in the food industry.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Liquid buttermilk is used primarily in the commercial preparation of baked goods and cheese.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Buttermilk solids are used in ice cream manufacturing, as well as being added to pancake mixes to make buttermilk pancakes.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Home cooks can use powdered buttermilk to give baked goods a higher rise, add tang to dips, marinades, and rubs without thinning them out, and as a topping for fruits and vegetables.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Traditional buttermilk has only trace levels of fat – less than 0.5 percent.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Modern commercially produced buttermilk made with whole milk is 88% water, 3% protein, 3% fat, and 5% carbohydrates (see table).
[src:by-product/buttermilk] In a reference amount of 100 g (3.5 oz) (100 ml), whole buttermilk provides 62 calories of food energy, and is a moderate source of vitamin B12 (19% DV) and riboflavin (13% DV, table).
[src:by-product/buttermilk] Acidified buttermilk or acidulated buttermilk is a substitute made by adding a food-grade acid, such as distilled white vinegar or lemon juice, to milk and letting it stand for about 10 minutes until it curdles.
[src:by-product/buttermilk] (About 15 millilitres (0.5 imperial fluid ounces; 0.5 US fluid ounces) of acid is added 200 to 250 ml (7 to 9 imp fl oz; 7 to 8 US fl oz) of milk.) Milk with any amount of fat can be used, but whole milk is usually used for baking.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Recycling is a key component of modern waste reduction and represents the third step in the "Reduce, Reuse, and Recycle" waste hierarchy, contributing to environmental sustainability and resource conservation.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It promotes environmental sustainability by removing raw material input and redirecting waste output in the economic system.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] There are some ISO standards related to recycling, such as ISO 15270:2008 for plastics waste and ISO 14001:2015 for environmental management control of recycling practice.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In ideal implementations, recycling a material produces a fresh supply of the same material—for example, used office paper would be converted into new office paper, and used polystyrene foam into new polystyrene.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Some types of materials, such as metal cans, can be remanufactured repeatedly without losing their purity.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] With other materials, this is often difficult or too expensive (compared with producing the same product from raw materials or other sources), so "recycling" of many products and materials involves their *reuse* in producing different materials (for example, paperboard).
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Another form of recycling is the salvage of constituent materials from complex products, due to either their intrinsic value (such as lead from car batteries and gold from printed circuit boards), or their hazardous nature (e.g. removal and reuse of mercury from thermometers and thermostats).
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] During periods when resources were scarce, archaeological studies of ancient waste dumps show less household waste (such as ash, broken tools, and pottery), implying that more waste was recycled in place of new material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] However, archaeological artefacts made from recyclable material, such as glass or metal, may neither be the original object nor resemble it, with the consequence that a successful ancient recycling economy can become invisible when recycling is synonymous with re-melting rather than reuse.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In pre-industrial times, there is evidence of scrap bronze and other metals being collected in Europe and melted down for continuous reuse.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Paper recycling was first recorded in 1031 when Japanese shops sold repulped paper.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In Britain dust and ash from wood and coal fires was collected by "dustmen" and downcycled as a base material for brick making.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] These forms of recycling were driven by the economic advantage of obtaining recycled materials instead of virgin material, and the need for waste removal in ever-more-densely populated areas.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In 1813, Benjamin Law developed the process of turning rags into "shoddy" and "mungo" wool in Batley, Yorkshire, which combined recycled fibers with virgin wool.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The West Yorkshire shoddy industry in towns such as Batley and Dewsbury lasted from the early 19th century to at least 1914.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Industrialization spurred demand for affordable materials.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In addition to rags, ferrous scrap metals were coveted as they were cheaper to acquire than virgin ore.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Railroads purchased and sold scrap metal in the 19th century, and the growing steel and automobile industries purchased scrap in the early 20th century.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Many secondary goods were collected, processed and sold by peddlers who scoured dumps and city streets for discarded machinery, pots, pans, and other sources of metal.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] By World War I, thousands of such peddlers roamed the streets of American cities, taking advantage of market forces to recycle post-consumer materials into industrial production.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Manufacturers of beverage bottles, including Schweppes, began offering refundable recycling deposits in Great Britain and Ireland around 1800.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] An official recycling system with refundable deposits for bottles was established in Sweden in 1884, and for aluminum beverage cans in 1982; it led to recycling rates of 84–99%, depending on type (glass bottles can be refilled around 20 times).
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] New chemical industries created in the late 19th century both invented new materials (e.g.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Bakelite in 1907) and promised to transform valueless into valuable materials.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Proverbially, you could not make a silk purse of a sow's ear—until the US firm Arthur D.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Little published in 1921 "On the Making of Silk Purses from Sows' Ears", its research proving that when "chemistry puts on overalls and gets down to business [...] new values appear.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Recycling—or "salvage", as it was then usually known—was a major issue for governments during World War II, where financial constraints and significant material shortages made it necessary to reuse goods and recycle materials.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] These resource shortages caused by the world wars, and other such world-changing events, greatly encouraged recycling.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It became necessary for most homes to recycle their waste, allowing people to make the most of what was available.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Recycling household materials also meant more resources were left available for war efforts.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Massive government campaigns, such as the National Salvage Campaign in Britain and the Salvage for Victory campaign in the United States, occurred in every fighting nation, urging citizens to donate metal, paper, rags, and rubber as a patriotic duty.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A considerable investment in recycling occurred in the 1970s due to rising energy costs.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Recycling aluminium uses only 5% of the energy of virgin production.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Glass, paper and other metals have less dramatic but significant energy savings when recycled.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Although consumer electronics have been popular since the 1920s, recycling them was almost unheard of until early 1991.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The first electronic waste recycling scheme was implemented in Switzerland, beginning with collection of old refrigerators, then expanding to cover all devices.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] When these programs were created, many countries could not deal with the sheer quantity of e-waste, or its hazardous nature, and began to export the problem to developing countries without enforced environmental legislation.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] (For example, recycling computer monitors in the United States costs 10 times more than in China.) Demand for electronic waste in Asia began to grow when scrapyards found they could extract valuable substances such as copper, silver, iron, silicon, nickel, and gold during the recycling process.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The 2000s saw a boom in both the sales of electronic devices and their growth as a waste stream: In 2002, e-waste grew faster than any other type of waste in the EU.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] This spurred investment in modern automated facilities to cope with the influx, especially after strict laws were implemented in 2003.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] As of 2014, the European Union had about 50% of world share of waste and recycling industries, with over 60,000 companies employing 500,000 people and a turnover of €24 billion.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] EU countries are mandated to reach recycling rates of at least 50%; leading countries are already at around 65%.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The overall EU average was 39% in 2013 and is rising steadily, to 45% in 2015.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In 2015, the United Nations General Assembly set 17 Sustainable Development Goals.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Goal 12, Responsible Consumption and Production, specifies 11 targets "to ensure sustainable consumption and production patterns".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The fifth target, Target 12.5, is defined as substantially reducing waste generation by 2030, indicated by the National Recycling Rate.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In 2018, changes in the recycling industry have sparked a global "crisis".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] On 31 December 2017, China announced its "National Sword" policy, setting new standards for imports of recyclable material and banning materials deemed too "dirty" or "hazardous".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The new policy caused drastic disruptions in the global recycling market, and reduced the prices of scrap plastic and low-grade paper.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Exports of recyclable materials from G7 countries to China dropped dramatically, with many shifting to countries in southeast Asia.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] This generated significant concern about the recycling industry's practices and environmental sustainability.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The abrupt shift caused countries to accept more materials than they could process, and raised fundamental questions about shipping waste from developed countries to countries with few environmental regulations—a practice that predated the crisis.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] According to the WHO (2023), "Every year millions of electrical and electronic devices are discarded ... a threat to the environment and to human health if they are not treated, disposed of, and recycled appropriately.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Common items ... include computers ... e-waste are recycled using environmentally unsound techniques and are likely stored in homes and warehouses, dumped, exported or recycled under inferior conditions.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Copper slag is obtained when copper and nickel ores are recovered from their source ores using a pyrometallurgical process, and these ores usually contain other elements which include iron, cobalt, silica, and alumina.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] An estimate of 2.2–3 tons of copper slag is generated per ton of copper produced, resulting in around 24.6 tons of slag per year, which is regarded as waste.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Environmental impact of slag include copper paralysis, which leads to death due to gastric hemorrhage, if ingested by humans.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It may also cause acute dermatitis upon skin exposure.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Toxicity may also be uptaken by crops through soil, consequently spreading animals and food sources and increasing the risk of cardiovascular diseases, cancer, cognitive impairment, chronic anemia, and damage to kidneys, bones, nervous system, brain and skin.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Substituting gravel and grit in quarries has been more cost-effective, due to having its sources with better proximity to consumer markets.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Trading between countries and establishment of blast furnaces is helping increase slag utilization, hence reducing wastage and pollution.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Economist Steven Landsburg, author of a paper entitled "Why I Am Not an Environmentalist", claimed that paper recycling actually reduces tree populations.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] He argues that because paper companies have incentives to replenish their forests, large demands for paper lead to large forests while reduced demand for paper leads to fewer "farmed" forests.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] When foresting companies cut down trees, more are planted in their place; however, such farmed forests are inferior to natural forests in several ways.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Farmed forests are not able to fix the soil as quickly as natural forests.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] This can cause widespread soil erosion and often requiring large amounts of fertilizer to maintain the soil, while containing little tree and wild-life biodiversity compared to virgin forests.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Also, the new trees planted are not as big as the trees that were cut down, and the argument that there would be "more trees" is not compelling to forestry advocates when they are counting saplings.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In particular, wood from tropical rainforests is rarely harvested for paper because of their heterogeneity.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] According to the United Nations Framework Convention on Climate Change secretariat, the overwhelming direct cause of deforestation is subsistence farming (48% of deforestation) and commercial agriculture (32%), which is linked to food, not paper production.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Other non-conventional methods of material recycling, like Waste-to-Energy (WTE) systems, have garnered increased attention in the recent past due to the polarizing nature of their emissions.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] While viewed as a sustainable method of capturing energy from material waste feedstocks by many, others have cited numerous explanations for why the technology has not been scaled globally.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] For a recycling program to work, a large, stable supply of recyclable material is crucial.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Three legislative options have been used to create such supplies: mandatory recycling collection, container deposit legislation, and refuse bans.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Mandatory collection laws set recycling targets for cities, usually in the form that a certain percentage of a material must be diverted from the city's waste stream by a target date.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The city is responsible for working to meet this target.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Container deposit legislation mandates refunds for the return of certain containers—typically glass, plastic and metal.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] When a product in such a container is purchased, a small surcharge is added that the consumer can reclaim when the container is returned to a collection point.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] These programs have succeeded in creating an average 80% recycling rate.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Despite such good results, the shift in collection costs from local government to industry and consumers has created strong opposition in some areas—for example, where manufacturers bear the responsibility for recycling their products.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In the European Union, the WEEE Directive requires producers of consumer electronics to reimburse the recyclers' costs.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] An alternative way to increase the supply of recyclates is to ban the disposal of certain materials as waste, often including used oil, old batteries, tires, and garden waste.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] This can create a viable economy for the proper disposal of the products.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Care must be taken that enough recycling services exist to meet the supply, or such bans can create increased illegal dumping.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Four forms of legislation have also been used to increase and maintain the demand for recycled materials: minimum recycled content mandates, utilization rates, procurement policies, and recycled product labeling.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Both minimum recycled content mandates and utilization rates increase demand by forcing manufacturers to include recycling in their operations.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Content mandates specify that a certain percentage of a new product must consist of recycled material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Utilization rates are a more flexible option: Industries can meet their recycling targets at any point of their operations, or even contract out recycling in exchange for tradable credits.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Opponents to these methods cite their large increase in reporting requirements, and claim that they rob the industry of flexibility.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Governments have used their own purchasing power to increase recycling demand through "procurement policies".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] These policies are either "set-asides", which reserve a certain amount of spending for recycled products; or "price preference" programs that provide larger budgets when recycled items are purchased.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Additional regulations can target specific cases: in the United States, for example, the Environmental Protection Agency mandates the purchase of oil, paper, tires and building insulation from recycled or re-refined sources whenever possible.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The final government regulation toward increased demand is recycled product labeling.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] When producers are required to label their packaging with the amount of recycled material it contains (including the packaging), consumers can make more educated choices.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Consumers with sufficient buying power can choose more environmentally conscious options, prompting producers to increase the recycled material in their products and increase demand.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Standardized recycling labeling can also have a positive effect on the supply of recyclates when it specifies how and where the product can be recycled.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Closed-loop recycling is generally regarded as more sustainable as it minimizes resource loss.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] "Recyclate" is a raw material sent to and processed in a waste recycling plant or materials-recovery facility so it can be used in the production of new materials and products.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] For example, plastic bottles can be made into plastic pellets and synthetic fabrics.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The quality of recyclates is one of the principal challenges for the success of a long-term vision of a green economy and achieving zero waste.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It generally refers to how much of it is composed of target material, versus non-target material and other non-recyclable material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Steel and other metals have intrinsically higher recyclate quality; it is estimated that two-thirds of all new steel comes from recycled steel.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Only target material is likely to be recycled, so higher amounts of non-target and non-recyclable materials can reduce the quantity of recycled products.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A high proportion of non-target and non-recyclable material can make it more difficult to achieve "high-quality" recycling; and if recyclate is of poor quality, it is more likely to end up being down-cycled or, in more extreme cases, sent to other recovery options or landfilled.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] For example, to facilitate the remanufacturing of clear glass products, there are tight restrictions for colored glass entering the re-melt process.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Another example is the downcycling of plastic, where products such as plastic food packaging are often downcycled into lower quality products, and do not get recycled into the same plastic food packaging.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The quality of recyclate not only supports high-quality recycling, but it can also deliver significant environmental benefits by reducing, reusing, and keeping products out of landfills.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] High-quality recycling can support economic growth by maximizing the value of waste material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Higher income levels from the sale of quality recyclates can return value significant to local governments, households and businesses.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Pursuing high-quality recycling can also promote consumer and business confidence in the waste and resource management sector, and may encourage investment in it.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] There are many actions along the recycling supply chain, each of which can affect recyclate quality.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Waste producers who place non-target and non-recyclable wastes in recycling collections can affect the quality of final recyclate streams, and require extra efforts to discard those materials at later stages in the recycling process.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Different collection systems can induce different levels of contamination.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] When multiple materials are collected together, extra effort is required to sort them into separate streams and can significantly reduce the quality of the final products.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Transportation and the compaction of materials can also make this more difficult.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Despite improvements in technology and quality of recyclate, sorting facilities are still not 100% effective in separating materials.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Storing materials outside, where they can become wet, can also cause problems for re-processors.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Further sorting steps may be required to satisfactorily reduce the amount of non-target and non-recyclable material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A number of systems have been implemented to collect recyclates from the general waste stream, occupying different places on the spectrum of trade-off between public convenience and government ease and expense.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The three main categories of collection are drop-off centers, buy-back centers and curbside collection.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] About two-thirds of the cost of recycling is incurred in the collection phase.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Curbside collection encompasses many subtly different systems, which differ mostly on where in the process the recyclates are sorted and cleaned.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The main categories are mixed waste collection, commingled recyclables, and source separation.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A waste collection vehicle generally picks up the waste.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In mixed waste collection, recyclates are collected mixed with the rest of the waste, and the desired materials are sorted out and cleaned at a central sorting facility.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In a commingled or single-stream system, recyclables are mixed but kept separate from non-recyclable waste.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] This greatly reduces the need for post-collection cleaning, but requires public education on what materials are recyclable.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Source separation is the other extreme, where each material is cleaned and sorted prior to collection.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It requires the least post-collection sorting and produces the purest recyclates.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] However, it incurs additional operating costs for collecting each material, and requires extensive public education to avoid recyclate contamination.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In Oregon, USA, Oregon DEQ surveyed multi-family property managers; about half of them reported problems, including contamination of recyclables due to trespassers such as transients gaining access to collection areas.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Source separation used to be the preferred method due to the high cost of sorting commingled (mixed waste) collection.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] However, advances in sorting technology have substantially lowered this overhead, and many areas that had developed source separation programs have switched to what is called *co-mingled collection*.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] At buy-back centers, separated, cleaned recyclates are purchased, providing a clear incentive for use and creating a stable supply.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The post-processed material can then be sold.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] If profitable, this conserves the emission of greenhouse gases; if unprofitable, it increases their emission.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Buy-back centres generally need government subsidies to be viable.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] National Waste & Recycling Association, it costs an average $50 to process a ton of material that can be resold for $30.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Drop-off centers require the waste producer to carry recyclates to a central location—either an installed or mobile collection station or the reprocessing plant itself.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] They are the easiest type of collection to establish but suffer from low and unpredictable throughput.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] For some waste materials such as plastic, recent technical devices called recyclebots enable a form of distributed recycling called DRAM (distributed recycling additive manufacturing).
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Preliminary life-cycle analysis (LCA) indicates that such distributed recycling of HDPE to make filament for 3D printers in rural regions consumes less energy than using virgin resin, or using conventional recycling processes with their associated transportation.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Another form of distributed recycling mixes waste plastic with sand to make bricks in Africa.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Several studies have looked at the properties of recycled waste plastic and sand bricks.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The composite pavers can be sold at 100% profit while employing workers at 1.5× the minimum wage in the West African region, where distributed recycling has the potential to produce 19 million pavement tiles from 28,000 tons of plastic water sachets annually in Ghana, Nigeria, and Liberia.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] This has also been done with COVID19 masks.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Once commingled recyclates are collected and delivered to a materials recovery facility, the materials must be sorted.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] This is done in a series of stages, many of which involve automated processes, enabling a truckload of material to be fully sorted in less than an hour.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Some plants can now sort materials automatically; this is known as single-stream recycling.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Automatic sorting may be aided by robotics and machine learning.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In plants, a variety of materials is sorted including paper, different types of plastics, glass, metals, food scraps, and most types of batteries.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A 30% increase in recycling rates has been seen in areas with these plants.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In the US, there are over 300 materials recovery facilities.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Initially, commingled recyclates are removed from the collection vehicle and placed on a conveyor belt spread out in a single layer.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Large pieces of corrugated fiberboard and plastic bags are removed by hand at this stage, as they can cause later machinery to jam.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Next, automated machinery such as disk screens and air classifiers separate the recyclates by weight, splitting lighter paper and plastic from heavier glass and metal.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Cardboard is removed from mixed paper, and the most common types of plastic—PET (#1) and HDPE (#2)—are collected, so these materials can be diverted into the proper collection channels.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] This is usually done by hand; but in some sorting centers, spectroscopic scanners are used to differentiate between types of paper and plastic based on their absorbed wavelengths.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Plastics tend to be incompatible with each other due to differences in chemical composition; their polymer molecules repel each other, similar to oil and water.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Strong magnets are used to separate out ferrous metals such as iron, steel and tin cans.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Non-ferrous metals are ejected by magnetic eddy currents: A rotating magnetic field induces an electric current around aluminum cans, creating an eddy current inside the cans that is repulsed by a large magnetic field, ejecting the cans from the stream.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Finally, glass is sorted according to its color: brown, amber, green, or clear.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It may be sorted either by hand, or by a machine that uses colored filters to detect colors.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Glass fragments smaller than 10 millimetres (0.39 in) cannot be sorted automatically, and are mixed together as "glass fines".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In 2003, San Francisco's Department of the Environment set a citywide goal of zero waste by 2020.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] San Francisco's refuse hauler, Recology, operates an effective recyclables sorting facility that has helped the city reach a record-breaking landfill diversion rate of 80% as of 2021.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Other American cities, including Los Angeles, have achieved similar rates.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Although many government programs concentrate on recycling at home, 64% of waste in the United Kingdom is generated by industry.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The focus of many recycling programs in industry is their cost-effectiveness.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The ubiquitous nature of cardboard packaging makes cardboard a common waste product recycled by companies that deal heavily in packaged goods, such as retail stores, warehouses, and goods distributors.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Other industries deal in niche and specialized products, depending on the waste materials they handle.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Glass, lumber, wood pulp and paper manufacturers all deal directly in commonly recycled materials; however, independent tire dealers may collect and recycle rubber tires for a profit.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The waste produced from burning coal in a Coal-fired power station is often called fuel ash or fly ash in the United States.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It is a very useful material and used in concrete construction.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Levels of metals recycling are generally low.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In 2010, the International Resource Panel, hosted by the United Nations Environment Programme (UNEP), published reports on metal stocks and their recycling rates.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It reported that the increase in the use of metals during the 20th and into the 21st century has led to a substantial shift in metal stocks from below-ground to use in above-ground applications within society.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] For example, in the US, in-use copper grew from 73 to 238 kg per capita between 1932–1999.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The report's authors observed that, as metals are inherently recyclable, metal stocks in society can serve as huge above-ground mines (the term "urban mining" has thus been coined).
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] However, they found that the recycling rates of many metals are low.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Navy's Ship Disposal Program uses ship breaking to reclaim the steel of old vessels.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Ships may also be sunk to create artificial reefs.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Uranium is a dense metal that has qualities superior to lead and titanium for many military and industrial uses.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Uranium left over from processing it into nuclear weapons and fuel for nuclear reactors is called depleted uranium, and is used by all branches of the U.S. military for the development of such things as armor-piercing shells and shielding.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The construction industry may recycle concrete and old road surface pavement, selling these materials for profit.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Some rapidly growing industries, particularly the renewable energy and solar photovoltaic technology industries, are proactively creating recycling policies even before their waste streams have considerable volume, anticipating future demand.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Recycling of plastics is more difficult, as most programs are not able to reach the necessary level of quality.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Recycling of PVC often results in downcycling of the material, which means only products of lower quality standard can be made with the recycled material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] E-waste is a growing problem, accounting for 20–50 million metric tons of global waste per year according to the EPA.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It is also the fastest growing waste stream in the EU.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Many recyclers do not recycle e-waste responsibly.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] After the cargo barge Khian Sea dumped 14,000 metric tons of toxic ash in Haiti, the Basel Convention was formed to stem the flow of hazardous substances into poorer countries.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] They created the e-Stewards certification to ensure that recyclers are held to the highest standards for environmental responsibility and to help consumers identify responsible recyclers.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It operates alongside other prominent legislation, such as the Waste Electrical and Electronic Equipment Directive of the EU and the United States National Computer Recycling Act, to prevent poisonous chemicals from entering waterways and the atmosphere.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In the recycling process, television sets, monitors, cell phones, and computers are typically tested for reuse and repaired.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] If broken, they may be disassembled for parts still having high value if labor is cheap enough.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Other e-waste is shredded to pieces roughly 10 centimetres (3.9 in) in size and manually checked to separate toxic batteries and capacitors, which contain poisonous metals.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The remaining pieces are further shredded to 10 millimetres (0.39 in) particles and passed under a magnet to remove ferrous metals.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] An eddy current ejects non-ferrous metals, which are sorted by density either by a centrifuge or vibrating plates.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Precious metals can be dissolved in acid, sorted, and smelted into ingots.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The remaining glass and plastic fractions are separated by density and sold to re-processors.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Television sets and monitors must be manually disassembled to remove lead from CRTs and the mercury backlight from LCDs.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Vehicles, solar panels and wind turbines can also be recycled.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] They often contain rare-earth elements (REE) and/or other critical raw materials.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] For electric car production, large amounts of REE's are typically required.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Whereas many critical raw elements and REE's can be recovered, environmental engineer Phillipe Bihouix Archived 6 September 2021 at the Wayback Machine reports that recycling of indium, gallium, germanium, selenium, and tantalum is still very difficult and their recycling rates are very low.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Plastic recycling is the process of recovering scrap or waste plastic and reprocessing the material into useful products, sometimes completely different in form from their original state.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] For instance, this could mean melting down soft drink bottles and then casting them as plastic chairs and tables.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] For some types of plastic, the same piece of plastic can only be recycled about 2–3 times before its quality decreases to the point where it can no longer be used.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Some plastics are remelted to form new plastic objects; for example, PET water bottles can be converted into polyester destined for clothing.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A disadvantage of this type of recycling is that the molecular weight of the polymer can change further and the levels of unwanted substances in the plastic can increase with each remelt.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A commercial-built recycling facility was sent to the International Space Station in late 2019.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The facility takes in plastic waste and unneeded plastic parts and physically converts them into spools of feedstock for the space station additive manufacturing facility used for in-space 3D printing.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] For some polymers, it is possible to convert them back into monomers, for example, PET can be treated with an alcohol and a catalyst to form a dialkyl terephthalate.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The terephthalate diester can be used with ethylene glycol to form a new polyester polymer, thus making it possible to use the pure polymer again.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In 2019, Eastman Chemical Company announced initiatives of methanolysis and syngas designed to handle a greater variety of used material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Another process involves the conversion of assorted polymers into petroleum by a much less precise thermal depolymerization process.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Such a process would be able to accept almost any polymer or mix of polymers, including thermoset materials such as vulcanized rubber tires and the biopolymers in feathers and other agricultural waste.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Like natural petroleum, the chemicals produced can be used as fuels or as feedstock.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A RESEM Technology plant of this type in Carthage, Missouri, US, uses turkey waste as input material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Gasification is a similar process but is not technically recycling since polymers are not likely to become the result.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Plastic Pyrolysis can convert petroleum based waste streams such as plastics into quality fuels, carbons.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In order to meet recyclers' needs while providing manufacturers a consistent, uniform system, a coding system was developed.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The recycling code for plastics was introduced in 1988 by the plastics industry through the Society of the Plastics Industry.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Because municipal recycling programs traditionally have targeted packaging—primarily bottles and containers—the resin coding system offered a means of identifying the resin content of bottles and containers commonly found in the residential waste stream.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In the United States, plastic products are printed with numbers 1–7 depending on the type of resin.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Type 1 (polyethylene terephthalate) is commonly found in soft drink and water bottles.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Type 2 (high-density polyethylene) is found in most hard plastics such as milk jugs, laundry detergent bottles, and some dishware.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Type 3 (polyvinyl chloride) includes items such as shampoo bottles, shower curtains, hula hoops, credit cards, wire jacketing, medical equipment, siding, and piping.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Type 4 (low-density polyethylene) is found in shopping bags, squeezable bottles, tote bags, clothing, furniture, and carpet.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Type 5 is polypropylene and makes up syrup bottles, straws, Tupperware, and some automotive parts.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Type 6 is polystyrene and makes up meat trays, egg cartons, clamshell containers, and compact disc cases.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Type 7 includes all other plastics such as bulletproof materials, 3- and 5-gallon water bottles, cell phone and tablet frames, safety goggles and sunglasses.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Having a recycling code or the chasing arrows logo on a material is not an automatic indicator that a material is recyclable but rather an explanation of what the material is.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Types 1 and 2 are the most commonly recycled.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Fiscal efficiency Sometimes cities have found recycling saves resources compared to other methods of disposal of waste.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Two years after New York City declared that implementing recycling programs would be "a drain on the city", New York City leaders realized that an efficient recycling system could save the city over $20 million.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Municipalities often see fiscal benefits from implementing recycling programs, largely due to the reduced landfill costs.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A study conducted by the Technical University of Denmark according to the Economist found that in 83 percent of cases, recycling is the most efficient method to dispose of household waste.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] However, a 2004 assessment by the Danish Environmental Assessment Institute concluded that incineration was the most effective method for disposing of drink containers, even aluminium ones.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Fiscal efficiency is separate from economic efficiency.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Economic analysis of recycling does not include what economists call externalities: unpriced costs and benefits that accrue to individuals outside of private transactions.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Examples include less air pollution and greenhouse gases from incineration and less waste leaching from landfills.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Without mechanisms such as taxes or subsidies, businesses and consumers following their private benefit would ignore externalities despite the costs imposed on society.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] If landfills and incinerator pollution is inadequately regulated, these methods of waste disposal appear cheaper than they really are, because part of their cost is the pollution imposed on people nearby.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Thus, advocates have pushed for legislation to increase demand for recycled materials.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The United States Environmental Protection Agency (EPA) has concluded in favor of recycling, saying that recycling efforts reduced the country's carbon emissions by a net 49 million metric tonnes in 2005.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In the United Kingdom, the Waste and Resources Action Programme stated that Great Britain's recycling efforts reduce CO2 emissions by 10–15 million tonnes a year.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The question for economic efficiency is whether this reduction is worth the extra cost of recycling and thus makes the artificial demand creates by legislation worthwhile.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Certain requirements must be met for recycling to be economically feasible and environmentally effective.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] These include an adequate source of recyclates, a system to extract those recyclates from the waste stream, a nearby factory capable of reprocessing the recyclates, and a potential demand for the recycled products.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] These last two requirements are often overlooked—without both an industrial market for production using the collected materials and a consumer market for the manufactured goods, recycling is incomplete and in fact only "collection".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Free-market economist Julian Simon remarked "There are three ways society can organize waste disposal: (a) commanding, (b) guiding by tax and subsidy, and (c) leaving it to the individual and the market".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] These principles appear to divide economic thinkers today.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Frank Ackerman favours a high level of government intervention to provide recycling services.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] He believes that recycling's benefit cannot be effectively quantified by traditional *laissez-faire* economics.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Allen Hershkowitz supports intervention, saying that it is a public service equal to education and policing.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] He argues that manufacturers should shoulder more of the burden of waste disposal.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Paul Calcott and Margaret Walls advocate the second option.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] A deposit refund scheme and a small refuse charge would encourage recycling but not at the expense of illegal dumping.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Kinnaman concludes that a landfill tax would force consumers, companies and councils to recycle more.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Most free-market thinkers detest subsidy and intervention, arguing that they waste resources.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The general argument is that if cities charge the full cost of garbage collection, private companies can profitably recycle any materials for which the benefit of recycling exceeds the cost (e.g. aluminum) and do not recycle other materials for which the benefit is less than the cost (e.g. glass).
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Cities, on the other hand, often recycle even when they not only do not receive enough for the paper or plastic to pay for its collection, but must actually pay private recycling companies to take it off of their hands.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Terry Anderson and Donald Leal think that all recycling programmes should be privately operated, and therefore would only operate if the money saved by recycling exceeds its costs.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Benjamin argues that it wastes people's resources and lowers the wealth of a population.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Certain countries trade in unprocessed recyclates.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Some have complained that the ultimate fate of recyclates sold to another country is unknown and they may end up in landfills instead of being reprocessed.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] According to one report, in America, 50–80 percent of computers destined for recycling are actually not recycled.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] There are reports of illegal-waste imports to China being dismantled and recycled solely for monetary gain, without consideration for workers' health or environmental damage.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Although the Chinese government has banned these practices, it has not been able to eradicate them.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In 2008, the prices of recyclable waste plummeted before rebounding in 2009.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Cardboard averaged about £53/tonne from 2004 to 2008, dropped to £19/tonne, and then went up to £59/tonne in May 2009.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] PET plastic averaged about £156/tonne, dropped to £75/tonne and then moved up to £195/tonne in May 2009.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Certain regions have difficulty using or exporting as much of a material as they recycle.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] This problem is most prevalent with glass: both Britain and the U.S. import large quantities of wine bottled in green glass.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Though much of this glass is sent to be recycled, outside the American Midwest there is not enough wine production to use all of the reprocessed material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] The extra must be downcycled into building materials or re-inserted into the regular waste stream.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] Similarly, the northwestern United States has difficulty finding markets for recycled newspaper, given the large number of pulp mills in the region as well as the proximity to Asian markets.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In other areas of the U.S., however, demand for used newsprint has seen wide fluctuation.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] In some U.S. states, a program called RecycleBank pays people to recycle, receiving money from local municipalities for the reduction in landfill space that must be purchased.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p01] It uses a single stream process in which all material is automatically sorted.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Much of the difficulty inherent in recycling comes from the fact that most products are not designed with recycling in mind.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] In the USA around 6 to 7 percent of plastic is recycled.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] The concept of sustainable design aims to solve this problem, and was laid out in the 2002 book *Cradle to Cradle: Remaking the Way We Make Things* by architect William McDonough and chemist Michael Braungart.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] They suggest that every product (and all packaging it requires) should have a complete "closed-loop" cycle mapped out for each component—a way in which every component either returns to the natural ecosystem through biodegradation or is recycled indefinitely.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] While recycling diverts waste from entering directly into landfill sites, current recycling misses the dispersive components.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Critics believe that complete recycling is impracticable as highly dispersed wastes become so diluted that the energy needed for their recovery becomes increasingly excessive.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] As with environmental economics, care must be taken to ensure a complete view of the costs and benefits involved.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] For example, paperboard packaging for food products is more easily recycled than most plastic, but is heavier to ship and may result in more waste from spoilage.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Economic expenses can incentivize fraud.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Critics dispute the net economic and environmental benefits of recycling over its costs, and suggest that proponents of recycling often make matters worse and suffer from confirmation bias.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] The amount of energy saved through recycling depends upon the material being recycled and the type of energy accounting that is used.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Correct accounting for this saved energy can be accomplished with life-cycle analysis using real energy values, and in addition, exergy, which is a measure of how much useful energy can be used.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] In general, it takes far less energy to produce a unit mass of recycled materials than it does to make the same mass of virgin materials.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Some scholars use emergy (spelled with an m) analysis, for example, budgets for the amount of energy of one kind (exergy) that is required to make or transform things into another kind of product or service.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Emergy calculations take into account economics that can alter pure physics-based results.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Using emergy life-cycle analysis researchers have concluded that materials with large refining costs have the greatest potential for high recycle benefits.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] However, recycling proponents point out that a second timber or logging truck is eliminated when paper is collected for recycling, so the net energy consumption is the same.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] An emergy life-cycle analysis on recycling revealed that fly ash, aluminum, recycled concrete aggregate, recycled plastic, and steel yield higher efficiency ratios, whereas the recycling of lumber generates the lowest recycle benefit ratio.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Hence, the specific nature of the recycling process, the methods used to analyse the process, and the products involved affect the energy savings budgets.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] It is difficult to determine the amount of energy consumed or produced in waste disposal processes in broader ecological terms, where causal relations dissipate into complex networks of material and energy flow.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] How much energy is used in recycling also depends on the type of material being recycled and the process used to do so.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Aluminium is generally agreed to use far less energy when recycled rather than being produced from scratch.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] The EPA states that "recycling aluminum cans, for example, saves 95 percent of the energy required to make the same amount of aluminum from its virgin source, bauxite." In 2009, more than half of all aluminium cans produced came from recycled aluminium.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Similarly, it has been estimated that new steel produced with recycled cans reduces greenhouse gas emissions by 75%.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Economist Steven Landsburg has suggested that the sole benefit of reducing landfill space is trumped by the energy needed and resulting pollution from the recycling process.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Others, however, have calculated through life-cycle assessment that producing recycled paper uses less energy and water than harvesting, pulping, processing, and transporting virgin trees.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] When less recycled paper is used, additional energy is needed to create and maintain farmed forests until these forests are as self-sustainable as virgin forests.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Other studies have shown that recycling in itself is inefficient to perform the "decoupling" of economic development from the depletion of non-renewable raw materials that is necessary for sustainable development.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] The international transportation or recycle material flows through "... different trade networks of the three countries result in different flows, decay rates, and potential recycling returns".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] As global consumption of a natural resources grows, their depletion is inevitable.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] The best recycling can do is to delay; complete closure of material loops to achieve 100 percent recycling of nonrenewables is impossible as micro-trace materials dissipate into the environment causing severe damage to the planet's ecosystems.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Historically, this was identified as the metabolic rift by Karl Marx, who identified the unequal exchange rate between energy and nutrients flowing from rural areas to feed urban cities that create effluent wastes degrading the planet's ecological capital, such as loss in soil nutrient production.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Energy conservation also leads to what is known as Jevon's paradox, where improvements in energy efficiency lowers the cost of production and leads to a rebound effect where rates of consumption and economic growth increases.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] The amount of money actually saved through recycling depends on the efficiency of the recycling program used to do it.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] The Institute for Local Self-Reliance argues that the cost of recycling depends on various factors, such as landfill fees and the amount of disposal that the community recycles.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] It states that communities begin to save money when they treat recycling as a replacement for their traditional waste system rather than an add-on to it and by "redesigning their collection schedules and/or trucks".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] In some cases, the cost of recyclable materials also exceeds the cost of raw materials.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Virgin plastic resin costs 40 percent less than recycled resin.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Comparing the market cost of recyclable material with the cost of new raw materials ignores economic externalities—the costs that are currently not counted by the market.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Creating a new piece of plastic, for instance, may cause more pollution and be less sustainable than recycling a similar piece of plastic, but these factors are not counted in market cost.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] A life cycle assessment can be used to determine the levels of externalities and decide whether the recycling may be worthwhile despite unfavorable market costs.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Alternatively, legal means (such as a carbon tax) can be used to bring externalities into the market, so that the market cost of the material becomes close to the true cost.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] The recycling of waste electrical and electronic equipment can create a significant amount of pollution.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] This problem is specifically occurrent in India and China.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Informal recycling in an underground economy of these countries has generated an environmental and health disaster.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] High levels of lead (Pb), polybrominated diphenylethers (PBDEs), polychlorinated dioxins, and furans, as well as polybrominated dioxins and furans (PCDD/Fs and PBDD/Fs), concentrated in the air, bottom ash, dust, soil, water, and sediments in areas surrounding recycling sites.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] These materials can make work sites harmful to the workers themselves and the surrounding environment.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] In some countries, recycling is performed by the entrepreneurial poor such as the karung guni, zabbaleen, the rag-and-bone man, waste picker, and junk man.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] With the creation of large recycling organizations that may be profitable, either by law or economies of scale, the poor are more likely to be driven out of the recycling and the remanufacturing job market.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] To compensate for this loss of income, a society may need to create additional forms of societal programs to help support the poor.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Like the parable of the broken window, there is a net loss to the poor and possibly the whole of a society to make recycling artificially profitable, e.g. through the law.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] However, in Brazil and Argentina, waste pickers/informal recyclers work alongside the authorities, in fully or semi-funded cooperatives, allowing informal recycling to be legitimized as a paid public sector job.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Because the social support of a country is likely to be less than the loss of income to the poor undertaking recycling, there is a greater chance for the poor to come in conflict with the large recycling organizations.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] This means fewer people can decide if certain waste is more economically reusable in its current form rather than being reprocessed.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Contrasted to the recycling poor, the efficiency of their recycling may actually be higher for some materials because individuals have greater control over what is considered "waste".
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] One labor-intensive underused waste is electronic and computer waste.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Because this waste may still be functional and wanted mostly by those on lower incomes, who may sell or use it at a greater efficiency than large recyclers.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Some recycling advocates believe that laissez-faire individual-based recycling does not cover all of society's recycling needs.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Thus, it does not negate the need for an organized recycling program.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Local government can consider the activities of the recycling poor as contributing to the ruining of property.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] In a study done by social psychologist Shawn Burn, it was found that personal contact with individuals within a neighborhood is the most effective way to increase recycling within a community.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] In her study, she had 10 block leaders talk to their neighbors and persuade them to recycle.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] A comparison group was sent fliers promoting recycling.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] It was found that the neighbors that were personally contacted by their block leaders recycled much more than the group without personal contact.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] As a result of this study, Shawn Burn believes that personal contact within a small group of people is an important factor in encouraging recycling.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Another study done by Stuart Oskamp examines the effect of neighbors and friends on recycling.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] It was found in his studies that people who had friends and neighbors that recycled were much more likely to also recycle than those who did not have friends and neighbors that recycled.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Many schools have created recycling awareness clubs in order to give young students an insight on recycling.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] These schools believe that the clubs actually encourage students to not only recycle at school but at home as well.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Recycling of metals varies extremely by type.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Titanium and lead have an extremely high recycling rates of over 90%.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Copper and cobalt have high rates of recycling around 75%.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Only about half of aluminum is recycled.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Most of the remaining metals have recycling rates of below 35%, while 34 types of metals have recycling rates of under 1%.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] "Between 1960 and 2000, the world production of plastic resins increased 25 times its original amount, while recovery of the material remained below 5 percent." Many studies have addressed recycling behaviour and strategies to encourage community involvement in recycling programs.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] However, recent studies have concluded that social pressure does not work in this context.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] One reason for this is that social pressure functions well in small group sizes of 50 to 150 individuals (common to nomadic hunter–gatherer peoples) but not in communities numbering in the millions, as we see today.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Another reason is that individual recycling does not take place in the public view.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Following the increasing popularity of recycling collection being sent to the same landfills as trash, some people kept on putting recyclables on the recyclables bin.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Art objects are more and more often made from recycled material.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] By extending the lifespan of goods, parts, and materials, a circular economy seeks to minimize waste and maximize resource utilization.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Advanced sorting techniques like optical and robotic sorting may separate and recover valuable materials from waste streams, lowering the requirement for virgin resources and accelerating the shift to a circular economy.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] Community engagement, such as education and awareness campaigns, may support the acceptance of recycling and reuse programs and encourage the usage of sustainable practices.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] One can lessen our influence on the environment, save natural resources, and generate economic possibilities by adopting a circular economy using cutting-edge sorting technology and community engagement.
[src:by-product/by-product-synergy-p02] According to Melati et al., to successfully transition to a circular economy, legislative and regulatory frameworks must encourage sustainable practices while addressing possible obstacles and difficulties in putting these ideas into action.
[src:by-product/by-product] A **by-product** or **byproduct** is a secondary product derived from a production process, manufacturing process or chemical reaction; it is not the primary product or service being produced.
[src:by-product/by-product] A by-product can be useful and marketable or it can be considered waste: for example, bran, which is a byproduct of the milling of wheat into refined flour, is sometimes composted or burned for disposal, but in other cases, it can be used as a nutritious ingredient in human food or animal feed.
[src:by-product/by-product] Gasoline was once a byproduct of oil refining that later became a desirable commercial product as motor fuel.
[src:by-product/by-product] The plastic used in plastic shopping bags also started as a by-product of oil refining.
[src:by-product/by-product] By-products are sometimes called **co-products** to indicate that although they are secondary, they are desired products.
[src:by-product/by-product] For example, hides and leather may be called co-products of beef production.
[src:by-product/by-product] There is no strict distinction between by-products and co-products.
[src:by-product/by-product] In the context of production, a by-product is the "output from a joint production process that is minor in quantity and/or net realizable value (NRV) when compared with the main products".
[src:by-product/by-product] Because they are deemed to have no influence on reported financial results, by-products do not receive allocations of joint costs.
[src:by-product/by-product] By-products also, by convention, are not inventoried, but the NRV from by-products is typically recognized as "other income", or as a reduction of joint production processing costs when the by-product is produced.
[src:by-product/by-product] While some chemists treat "by-product" and "side-product" as synonyms in the above sense of a generic secondary (untargeted) product, others find it useful to distinguish between the two.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] The **germ** of a cereal grain is the part that develops into a plant; it is the seed embryo.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] Along with bran, germ is often a by-product of the milling that produces refined grain products.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] Cereal grains and their components, such as wheat germ oil, rice bran oil, and maize bran, may be used as a source from which vegetable oil is extracted, or used directly as a food ingredient.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] The germ is retained as an integral part of whole-grain foods.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] Non-whole grain methods of milling are intended to isolate the endosperm, which is ground into flour, with removal of both the husk (bran) and the germ.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] Removal of bran produces a flour with a white rather than a brown color and eliminates fiber.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] The germ is rich in polyunsaturated fats (which have a tendency to oxidize and become rancid on storage) and so germ removal improves the storage qualities of flour.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] Wheat germ or wheatgerm is a concentrated source of several essential nutrients, including vitamin E, folate (folic acid), phosphorus, thiamin, zinc, and magnesium, as well as essential fatty acids and fatty alcohols.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] White bread is made using flour that has had the germ and bran removed.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] Wheat germ can be added to protein shakes, casseroles, muffins, pancakes, cereals, yogurt, smoothies, cookies, and other goods.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] Wheat germ can become rancid if not properly stored in a refrigerator or freezer and away from sunlight.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] Some manufacturers prevent rancidity by storing wheat germ in vacuum-sealed glass containers, or by placing an oxygen-absorbing sachet inside air-tight packaging.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] In molecular biology, wheat germ extract is used to carry out cell-free *in vitro* translation experiments: the plant embryo contains all the macromolecular components necessary for translating mRNA into proteins, but relatively low levels of its own mRNA.
[src:by-product/cereal-germ] Wheat germ is also useful in biochemistry since it contains lectins that bind strongly to certain glycoproteins; therefore, it can be used to isolate such proteins.
